# config/domains.conf.example
#
# Copy this file to config/domains.conf and edit it with the mail domains you
# plan to host on this system.
#
# This file exists to make multi-domain hosting explicit and easy to understand.
# The project is designed so one OpenBSD mail host can serve one or more
# domains, as long as DNS, TLS, DKIM, mailbox routing, and account definitions
# are configured correctly in later phases.
#
# Key ideas:
# - PRIMARY_DOMAIN is the main administrative and reference domain
# - DOMAINS is the full list of domains the server will host
# - domains should be separated by spaces
# - every domain listed here must later receive its own DNS records
# - every hosted domain will later need DKIM, SPF, DMARC, MX, and mailbox policy
#
# Single-domain example:
#   PRIMARY_DOMAIN="example.com"
#   DOMAINS="example.com"
#
# Multi-domain example:
#   PRIMARY_DOMAIN="example.com"
#   DOMAINS="example.com example.net example.org"
#
# In the multi-domain example above:
# - example.com is the primary domain
# - example.net and example.org are additional hosted domains
# - all three domains will later need to be added to PostfixAdmin and the mail
#   routing tables
#
# Advanced note:
# Later phases can use this list to generate or validate SQL domain records,
# DKIM selectors, DNS output, and hosted mailbox policy.

PRIMARY_DOMAIN="example.com"
DOMAINS="example.com example.net example.org"
